## **Introduction**

This document will function as a first introduction to the ShipRec web application, a site that aims to present the location of ships as tracked by the AIS system in a more user friendly way, as well as to provide some quality of life functions to anyone interested in viewing the travels of our sea traversing machinery.  
    
This specific document version (1.3) will explore the design requirements of our application and some early design decisions.

## **Project Scope**

ShipRec is designed to display the positions of ships in an easy to read map, which will allow the user to select the time they want to inspect (within a range of 6 months from current time) and track ships through time. The application will also provide all necessary data for any specific ship, like the ship’s type, speed, direction and so on. In our system, users will have the ability to register and receive access to more functions. These functions include tracking specific ships, filtering the ships shown in the map based on user’s criteria, creating fleets of ships to monitor in the map, creating specific zones of interest in the map of which one can be actively observed at a time and receiving notifications for events of interest.  
   
When installing the system, the owners will have the ability to create administrator accounts, which will have the ability to change the statistics of ships in addition to having all other abilities a registered user has.

No user will be able to add or remove ships from the system, as all ships must be in the AIS data the site reads and displays.  
   
The application will also not provide any social or business interaction. Users will not be displayed in the system, as the concept of a user only exists to help store the preferences of anyone who wishes to use the application.

The complete list of functions available in our application is described later in this document.

## 

## **User Roles** 

The app has been designed to accommodate three user roles:

1. **Non Registered Users**  
   These are the users that have either not created an account or not signed in the app. They have limited access to the app’s features. In order to gain access to every feature available in the app, the user has to create an account and log in. Non registered users will be able to perform the following functions:  
* View the map and the ships in it.  
* View the details of any selected ship(Type, company, position, etc)  
* View the functions available to registered users and sign up or login.  
2. **Registered Users**  
   These are the users that have created an account and signed in the app. They are able to perform the same functions as the non-registered users, as well as the following:  
* Track the trajectory of any ship for a given time period.  
* Create custom fleets by saving ships of interest  
* Filter out the ships displayed on the map (Based on company, type, etc)  
* Set zones of interest and constraints for each zone (like max speed of ships, or types of ships passing)  
* Get notifications whenever a constraint is violated.  
* Submit questions to the admins related to the functionality of the application.  
3. **Administrators**

	These users are generated at the creation of the app and have the same permissions as   
	any registered user. In addition, they can perform the following actions:

* Modify the type of any vessel.  
* View and ban any users that don’t comply with the terms and conditions of the application. Banned users have the same rights as the non-registered users. Banning a user can be reversed.  
* View any questions submitted by registered users.

## 

## **Functional Requirements**

Functional requirements of the app have been split into the following categories:

* **Authentication**

	To be authenticated a user must exist in the app’s database.

* New users must sign up using their email, a password, their first and last name and their country.  
  * Users who already have an account must login using their email and password.

  After logging in users stay authenticated for a set amount of time with the use of a JSON       Web Token (JWT).


* **Authorization**  
  There are three access levels for users, each defined by the user’s role. Depending on the role the access levels are as follows:  
  * **Minimum Access \- Non-Registered User**

  Non-registered users are all non authenticated users.

    * Users must be able to view the map.  
    * Users must be able to view a vessel’s data (name, company, etc.) when clicking on it.  
    * Users must be able to search for information on the map and use all filters except “My Fleets”.  
    * Users must be able to switch between light and dark mode.  
    * Users must be able to access the “Help” feature.

  * **Normal Access \- Registered User**  
    Registered users are all authenticated users who are not administrators. They have access to everything non-registered users do as well as:  
    * Users must be able to select and group different vessels on the map into fleets.  
    * Users must be able to edit and name their fleets.  
    * Users must be able to select and save areas on the map to monitor.  
    * Users must be able to edit their selected areas.  
    * Users must be able to use filters to only look at specific vessel types.  
    * Users must be able to edit their profile and change their personal information in it.  
    * Users must be able to delete their account on the app.  
    * Users must be able to view a list of vessels on the map on the “Vessels” page.  
    * Users must be able to view a list of ports on the map on the “Ports” page.  
    * Users must be able to view information and updates on their saved areas and fleets on the “My Collection” page.  
    * Users must receive notifications on the activity of their selected fleets and areas.  
    * Users must be able to filter the notifications they receive.  
    * Users must be able to send messages to the app’s administrators.  
        
  * **Full Access \- Administrator**

  Administrators are registered users with special privileges in the app’s data.

    * Administrators must be able to edit the type of any selected ship.  
    * Administrators must be able to ban/unban any user.  
    * Administrators must be able to delete banned users.  
    * Administrators must be able to view user’s messages.  
        
* **Data Processing**  
  The app processes six-month historic AIS data obtained from Zenodo for functions that require this information, like displaying ships live on the map, and stores its own data in a MySQL relational database.  
  * The app must be able to receive AIS vessel data in real time logs and dynamically update the live map accordingly without needing to refresh the page.    
  * The app must store the email, first name, last name and country that every new user inserts at the sign-up process, in a User table inside the database. Passwords are stored as secure, non-reversible hashes using a cryptographic password hashing algorithm. A user id is also produced.  
  * The app must successfully grant access in a user’s account after they enter the user’s email and its corresponding password correctly at the sign-in phase, after hashing the password and checking the user’s entry in the database for correctness.   
  * The app must allow users to update the above information in the database if they decide to change them.   
  * The app must filter the objects that appear on the live map according to the filters that the user has selected at each moment, in combination with what is typed on the search bar at this same moment (which may be an object’s name or a number identifying it, e.g. IMO number for ships).   
  * The app must update the academic institution, company, and phone number for any user that decides to add or change this information by editing their accounts.   
  * The app must store the fleets made by the users in a table of the database, matching each fleet to the user that created it and the list of objects (vessels) it contains.   
  * The app must store the areas created by users in a table of the database, matching each area to the user that created it and the borders that the user set for the area. The borders of areas will be rectangles, so there is the option of matching each area to the 4 points that make the rectangle, or the 2 diagonal points, in the form of coordinates.   
  * The app must have a way to store history of the information it receives in real time, firstly because we need the user to be able to see previous movement of vessels for the past 12 hours at any moment, and secondly because we want to ensure that even in case of server failure there will be no loss of previous data when the issue is fixed. For this purpose we use an event streaming platform to buffer the data. 

* **User Interface and User Experience (UI/UX)**

The following have been decided to maximize good user experience:

* **Login Page**  
  * Users must be able to login using their email and password.  
    * Forgot password feature so users can reset their password.  
    * Prompt for users without accounts to sign up with an appropriate link to the sign up page.  
        
  * **Sign Up Page**  
    * Users must be able to create an account in the app by using their email, a password, their first and last name and their country.  
    * Prompt for users with accounts to login with an appropriate link to the login page.  
        
        
        
  * **Map Page**  
    * Users can zoom in and zoom out on the map to look at smaller or broader areas.  
    * Users must be able to search for vessels, ports, etc. on the map by using any keyword. Filters can be applied to the search before and after it is made.  
    * Users must be able to filter the type of vessels appearing on the map.  
    * When users click on a vessel they must be able to see its name, type, speed, course and how close it is to its destination.  
    * Registered users must be able to track a vessel’s past and future course on the map.  
    * When registered users click on a vessel they must be able to add the vessel to their fleet.  
    * Users can enter Select Mode when clicking on the appropriate button.  
    * Users must be able to select an area on the map by clicking and dragging their mouse over it when in Select Mode.  
    * Users must be able to save the area they selected.  
    * Users must be able to toggle between light and dark mode depending on their preference.  
    * Users must be able to go to vessel/port details pages by clicking on the corresponding button that pops up when clicking on a vessel or port.  
        
  * **Vessel Details**  
    * Users must be able to add vessel to a new or preexisting fleet.  
    * Users view a vessel’s details.  
        
  * **Port Details**  
    * Users must be able to add restrictions to the port and receive notifications when they are not met.  
    * Users must be able to view a port’s details.  
        
  * **Vessels Page**  
    * Users must be able to search for specific vessels and apply filters to their search.  
    * Users must be able to view any vessel on the map by clicking on the corresponding button.  
    * Vessels must appear in paged format instead of scrolling.  
    * Users must be able to select one or all vessels on screen and choose to add them to a new fleet or one of their pre-existing ones.  
    * Users must be able to sort the vessels on screen by ascending or descending order of any column.  
    * Users must be able to move to the Vessel Details page for any vessel by clicking on the vessel's name.  
        
  * **Ports Page**  
    * Users must be able to search for specific ports and apply filters to their search.  
    * Users must be able to view any port on the map by clicking on the corresponding button.  
    * Ports must appear in paged format instead of scrolling.  
    * Users must be able to sort the ports on screen by ascending or descending order of any column.  
    * Users must be able to move to the Port Details page for any port by clicking on the port’s name.  
        
  * **My Account Page**

  This page has been divided into the following tabs:

    * My Profile  
      * Users must be able to edit their first and last name, their country, academic institution, business and phone number after clicking the Edit Account button.  
    * My Fleets  
      * Users must be able to view their pre-existing fleets.  
      * Users must be able to view and edit any fleet by clicking on the corresponding button.  
      * Users can view how many of a fleet's vessels are active.  
      * Users must be able to view any of their fleets on the map by clicking the corresponding button.  
      * Users must be able to create a new fleet by clicking the corresponding button.  
      * Users must be able to add a vessel to one of their fleets by clicking the corresponding button.  
      * Users must be able to select any or all of their fleets and delete them.  
      * Users must be able to name their fleets.  
      * Users must be able to set any vessel in a fleet as active or inactive by clicking the corresponding toggle when editing the fleet.  
      * Fleets must appear in paged format instead of scrolling.  
    * My Areas  
      * Users must be able to view their saved areas of the map and set them as active or inactive with the corresponding toggle.  
      * Users must be able to set a color for each of their areas.  
      * Users must be able to select and save a new area on the map by clicking the corresponding button.  
      * Users must be able to view any of their saved areas on the map by clicking the corresponding button.  
      * Users must be able to select any or all of their areas and delete them.  
      * Areas must appear in paged format instead of scrolling.  
      * Users must be able to set restrictions for their areas for speed or cargo. If the restrictions are not met, a notification is sent.  
    * My Notifications  
      * Users must be able to filter through their notifications by type or see all of them by clicking on the appropriate option on the side of the screen.  
      * Users must be able to sort their notifications from newest to oldest and vice versa.  
      * Users must be able to select any or all notifications and delete them.  
      * Notifications must appear in paged format instead of scrolling.

  * **Settings Page**  
* Users must be able to change their email.  
* Users must be able to change their password.  
* Password needed for email change.  
* Old password needed for password change and new password needed twice.  
* Users must be able to delete their account.  
* “Are you sure?” prompt when a user tries to delete their account.  
* Toggle to turn on/off email notifications.

  * **Help Page**  
    This page has been divided into the following tabs:  
    * Frequently Asked Questions (FAQ)  
      * Users must be able to view already asked questions.  
      * Users must be able to view answers to the questions when clicking on them.  
    * Contact Us  
      * Users must be able to send a message to the app’s administrators with their questions. To send the message their first and last name is required as well as their email and phone number.

    

  * **Administrator Page**  
    This page has been divided into the following tabs:  
    * Users  
      * Administrators must be able to ban any user.  
      * Administrators must be able to select one or all of the banned users and delete their accounts.  
      * Administrators must be able to unban any banned user.  
      * Administrators must be able to search for a specific user.  
    * Vessels  
      * Administrators must be able to change the type of any vessel.  
      * Administrators must be able to search for any vessel and apply filters to their search.  
      * Administrators must be able to sort vessels in ascending or descending order based on any column.  
      * Administrators must be able to choose any or all vessels and see them on the map by clicking on the corresponding button.  
    * Messages  
      * Administrators must be able to view messages from users by clicking on the appropriate button on each message.  
      * Administrators must be able to select any or all messages and delete them.  
      * Administrators must be able to choose whether or not they want email notifications for user queries by clicking on the corresponding toggle.

      

  * **Universal**  
    * Upon entering the app, users must immediately be able to view the map, without having to sign up. More features require sign up/login.  
    * Collapsible sidebar with navigation menu to maximize usable screen space.  
    * If a non-registered user attempts to use a feature only for registered users, they are prompted to login or sign up.   
    * Users must be able to return to the previous page by clicking on the Return button. This does not apply to the map page.  
    * Users must be able to sign out of the app.

* **System Integration**  
  The app consists of multiple layers, each one communicating with the ones next to it and properly transmitting data.  
  * The app shall implement a RESTful API to allow the frontend to securely fetch initial data from the backend. Additionally, it shall use WebSockets to provide real-time updates without requiring full-page reloads.  
  * The app shall ensure proper data exchange (reading and writing) between the backend part of the app and the relational database that will be used for storing and updating information useful for the app’s functions.  
  * The app shall integrate an event streaming platform to process and distribute real-time AIS data efficiently. This ensures that incoming ship position updates are immediately available to the frontend without frequent database queries. The event streaming system buffers incoming messages, preventing data loss during temporary server failures and allowing different parts of the system to consume data asynchronously at their own pace.  
  * The app shall integrate a third-party mapping API to display a real-time map with moving ships and other objects. AIS data updates ship positions dynamically. 


* **Error Handling and Logging**  
  The app needs to ensure the data received from users is correct, prevent errors and inform the user when something goes wrong. In case of difficulty in retrieving requested information it can attempt to try again before displaying an error message.   
    
  * The app shall check for a valid email string on the input at the sign-up process, and display a message indicating that the email inserted is not a valid email address.  
  * During sign-in, if no account exists for the provided email, the app shall display an error message indicating that the email is not associated with an account. If an account exists but the password is incorrect, a separate error message must be displayed.  
  * The app should ensure each area created by the user is highlighted with a different color than the others. This is done by only allowing the user to choose between colors that were not used for another area whenever they create a new area.   
  * The app shall display a popup warning before a user attempts deleting their account, informing them of the permanent data loss and the irreversibility of the act, this way predicting the consequences of any misclicks.   
  * The app shall inform the user whenever there is a difficulty or delay of fetching requested data or loading pages, with a loading indicator. When a time limit of waiting is exceeded or after a predetermined amount of failed fetching attempts have happened, the app should inform with a popup indicating that something went wrong and encouraging to try again, and then return to the previous state or page.

## **Non-functional Requirements**

Non-functional requirements are crucial to the product’s success. Specifically, we need to take into account the following.

*      **Product Availability**  
  Availability is a metric that measures the probability that a system is not failed, or undergoing a repair when it needs to be used. With that in mind:  
  * Our system needs to have the best possible availability, realistically around 99%, so that the 1% can be used for repairs when they are undoubtedly needed.  
  * We need to provide our system with mechanisms to recover from failures quickly, like automatic backups of information, and failover techniques so the website can return to its original state.   
  * In case of a major system failure, the recovery time must not be over an hour.

* **Performance Requirements**

The product needs to have high performance at all times, to support all of its users in real-time. 

* It should support at least 10.000 concurrent users, with all of their orders issued on the platform and without lagging.  
  * The response time must be less than 200ms for the most important operations, like searching for a ship, viewing ship information, tracking a ship in real-time, as well as alerts for collisions.   
  *  Less necessary components can be generated with optimal loading on the front-end.

* **Safety & Security Requirements**

Safeguards must be taken for the safety of the platform to be ensured. Specifically:

* The automatic backups mentioned above can help reduce the danger of data loss and damage, so users can recover their information.   
  * To ensure that the data of the ships themselves remains intact, security must be implemented so that only the administrator users can modify it.   
  * The software must comply with maritime safety rules according to *IMO (International Maritime Organization)* and *SOLAS (Safety of Life at Sea),* for the ships to navigate safely and legally.  
  * It must also comply with the charting standards of *IHO (International Hydrographic Organization).*  
  * Concerning the platform’s security, the ships’ data must be compliant with *ISO 27001* *(Information Security according to Global Standards)* and stored according to *GDPR (General Data Protection Regulation),* since these are the security regulations in Europe.  


*     **Flexibility & Scalability** 

The software must be flexible so that new aspects can be added without much trouble and without core system changes. This can be done by using modular architecture, plus :

* The platform must be a **Single-Page Application (SPA),** which contributes to easier updates. It should provide the map using resources like *Leaflet.js.*  
  * Scalability will be provided by catering to each user type with personalized profile pages / dashboards where they can see their saved information and collections.  
  * Real-time data processing must be done using **Apache Kafka** to handle AIS data streams efficiently.   
  * There should be a stable back-end to the software.  
      
*      **Efficiency**

For better system efficiency, the system should use as few resources as possible while achieving the best possible performance (mentioned above).

*  Less strain on the CPU can be achieved by using caching or conducting optimal queries on the database.  
  * Under normal user activity, CPU and memory usage should not exceed 80%.  
  * Under heavy user activity, the platform should maintain high performance and load the entirety of the map, and each page, in less than 300ms.  
      
*     **Compliance with International Standards**  
  * The platform must support *RESTFUL APIs (OpenAPI 3.0)* and the *WebSocket* protocol that was standardized by the IETF as RFC 6455 in 2011\.  
  * In compliance with International System Standards, the platform must follow *IMO SOLAS Regulation V/19,  IMO SOLAS Regulation V/9, RESTful API (OpenAPI 3.0) & GraphQL , ISO 25010 (Software Quality), ISO 22301 (Business Continuity), ISO 9001 (Quality Management).*  
  * The platform must comply with nautical standards and measurement units according to the SI, including miles per hour and nautical miles **(NM),**   
  * It must also support **Unicode & UTF-8** Encoding for international users and information, coordinates in degrees, minutes and seconds **(DMS)** for the geographical information.  
  * Every vessel on the platform must have a **MMSI,** or **Maritime Mobile Service Identity**. This is a maritime object's international *maritime telephone number*, a temporarily assigned UID issued by that object's current flag state. An MMSI comprises a series of nine digits, consisting of three Maritime Identification Digits (country-codes), concatenated with a specific identifier. Whenever an object is re-flagged, a new MMSI must be assigned.
